39
00:02:17.960 --> 00:02:21.620
So today, I'm going to share our recent work on digital tissue twins,

40
00:02:21.940 --> 00:02:25.900
and in particular, how to turn histology into spatial omics at the population

41
00:02:25.980 --> 00:02:26.260
scale.

42
00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:33.260
Spatial omics technologies, including spatial transcriptomics and

43
00:02:33.380 --> 00:02:36.959
spatial proteomics, have transformed our understanding of tumor

44
00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:40.640
ecosystems. However, despite their power, the

45
00:02:40.700 --> 00:02:44.100
current spatial technologies remain expensive and slow,

46
00:02:44.670 --> 00:02:48.480
and this makes them difficult to scale across the full clinical

47
00:02:48.580 --> 00:02:49.180
enterprise.

48
00:02:50.080 --> 00:02:53.980
So for example, just mounting a small piece of tissue can easily cost you

49
00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:57.800
a few thousand dollars. But on the other hand, many of the

50
00:02:57.840 --> 00:03:01.660
spatial omics platforms allow the generation of a histology image from the

51
00:03:01.700 --> 00:03:05.520
same tissue slice. And oftentimes, these histology images are

52
00:03:05.560 --> 00:03:09.380
very high resolution, high quality, and importantly, these

53
00:03:09.500 --> 00:03:13.340
histology images are very inexpensive, and indeed, they are already

54
00:03:13.400 --> 00:03:17.040
routinely being generated for nearly every cancer patient in the

55
00:03:17.060 --> 00:03:17.520
clinic.

56
00:03:18.460 --> 00:03:22.040
So this highlights a fundamental data tradeoff issue in spatial

57
00:03:22.060 --> 00:03:25.800
biology. On one hand, spatial omics is molecular

58
00:03:25.860 --> 00:03:29.440
information-rich but is expensive and slow, difficult to

59
00:03:29.600 --> 00:03:29.880
scale.

60
00:03:30.720 --> 00:03:34.600
On the other hand, digital pathology is common, cheap, and fast, but

61
00:03:34.640 --> 00:03:36.109
contains no molecular information.

62
00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:40.980
So a central question that the field is facing right now is: how can we

63
00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:41.900
bridge this gap?

64
00:03:42.880 --> 00:03:46.740
And this central question has motivated our development of what I

65
00:03:46.840 --> 00:03:50.640
call the digital tissue twins, where our goal is to transform

66
00:03:50.680 --> 00:03:54.360
those routine H&amp;E slides into spatially resolved and

67
00:03:54.460 --> 00:03:58.400
molecularly informed digital representation of human tissues at the

68
00:03:58.480 --> 00:04:01.620
population scale so that we can link spatial biology,

69
00:04:02.020 --> 00:04:05.880
AI, and clinical outcomes together to enable risk

70
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:09.300
prediction, patient stratification, and eventually

71
00:04:09.380 --> 00:04:11.000
therapeutic decision-making.

72
00:04:12.220 --> 00:04:15.660
So in the last few years, my lab has been developing this AI-powered

73
00:04:15.840 --> 00:04:19.700
ecosystem to help us build what I call the digital tissue twins.

74
00:04:20.579 --> 00:04:23.380
In this ecosystem, we start from H&amp;E stained

75
00:04:24.140 --> 00:04:27.700
histology images. We have developed the tools that can conduct the

76
00:04:27.840 --> 00:04:31.600
H&amp;E QC and the cellular resolution tissue masking,

77
00:04:31.800 --> 00:04:35.380
and the cellular resolution histopathology image segmentation.

78
00:04:36.260 --> 00:04:40.230
And leveraging these processed histology images, we also have developed

79
00:04:40.340 --> 00:04:43.980
tools that can help researchers to automatically select the

80
00:04:44.040 --> 00:04:47.420
most informative samples and the regions of interest for the

81
00:04:47.460 --> 00:04:49.600
expensive spatial omics experiments.

82
00:04:50.340 --> 00:04:54.000
And after the spatial omics data are generated, we can further leverage these

83
00:04:54.180 --> 00:04:58.040
histology images to enhance the quality of the spatial omics data.

84
00:04:58.840 --> 00:05:02.480
And after all of this data preparation is being done, we will build AI

85
00:05:02.500 --> 00:05:06.040
models to virtually predict the spatial omics data at the

86
00:05:06.080 --> 00:05:09.760
population scale. In the meantime, we also perform multi-modal

87
00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:12.800
data integration so that we can have a comprehensive

88
00:05:12.940 --> 00:05:16.520
representation of every single tissue section in every single

89
00:05:16.600 --> 00:05:16.960
patient.

90
00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:21.460
And throughout this inference and integration process, we use

91
00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:25.690
rigorous statistical modeling to ensure that the AI models that

92
00:05:25.720 --> 00:05:27.900
we build are reliable and are trustworthy.

93
00:05:29.140 --> 00:05:32.740
So the core idea behind building digital tissue twins is teaching

94
00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:35.460
AI to see molecules within a histology image.

95
00:05:36.130 --> 00:05:39.840
And this is based on a simple but powerful observation that is

96
00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:42.800
similar histology implies a similar molecular profile.

97
00:05:43.340 --> 00:05:47.020
So this means that if we can ask the AI to learn this link,

98
00:05:47.500 --> 00:05:50.980
then the histology images can become proxies of the spatial

99
00:05:51.100 --> 00:05:54.680
molecular marvelous that people typically obtain in the expensive

100
00:05:54.740 --> 00:05:56.110
spatial omics experiment.

101
00:05:57.070 --> 00:05:59.969
So our work in this space started back in 2021.

102
00:06:00.500 --> 00:06:04.200
We were among the first to treat the histology as a primary modality in

103
00:06:04.280 --> 00:06:07.810
spatial omics analysis.And then later we developed the

104
00:06:07.880 --> 00:06:11.860
iSTAR, where we used a hierarchical vision transformer to extract

105
00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:14.200
image features out of a histology image.

106
00:06:14.740 --> 00:06:18.660
And this mimics how a pathologist examines a histology slide under the

107
00:06:18.700 --> 00:06:19.300
microscope.

108
00:06:20.290 --> 00:06:24.050
And after the image features are extracted, we further leverage these

109
00:06:24.240 --> 00:06:27.680
image features to enhance the spatial resolution of gene expression

110
00:06:27.740 --> 00:06:30.700
data to single cell level. So for example,

111
00:06:31.380 --> 00:06:34.530
medium does not provide a single cell resolution gene expression.

112
00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:38.540
By using iSTAR, we can spatially enhance the resolution to single

113
00:06:38.580 --> 00:06:42.280
cell level. So importantly, iSTAR demonstrated

114
00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:46.140
that we can now turn a routinely obtained H&amp;E slide into

115
00:06:46.320 --> 00:06:49.960
single cell resolution spatial omics profiles.

116
00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:53.520
And building upon the success of iSTAR, we later developed the

117
00:06:53.620 --> 00:06:57.460
iSCALE, which utilized the virtual prediction idea

118
00:06:57.470 --> 00:07:01.270
to scale up spatial transcriptomics for larger sized tissues that

119
00:07:01.400 --> 00:07:05.340
far exceed the capture areas of conventional spatial omics platforms.

120
00:07:05.980 --> 00:07:09.540
And this framework is generic. It can be applied to any tissue types

121
00:07:09.860 --> 00:07:13.700
of any size as long as you can measure a H&amp;E stained histology

122
00:07:13.800 --> 00:07:17.220
image. So basically, by doing this innovative computational

123
00:07:17.320 --> 00:07:21.280
analysis, we can turn a task that is experimentally impossible

124
00:07:21.620 --> 00:07:23.980
into something that is computationally feasible.

125
00:07:24.940 --> 00:07:28.230
So last year, we further leveraged the relationship between tissue

126
00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:32.160
morphology and molecular profiles to develop this new tool

127
00:07:32.240 --> 00:07:35.880
called i2Omics, where we wanted to use AI to assist

128
00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:39.910
biologists to automatically select the most informative regions of

129
00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:42.520
interest for the expensive spatial omics experiments.

130
00:07:42.970 --> 00:07:46.840
So by doing so, we ensure that you can target

131
00:07:46.880 --> 00:07:50.800
your expensive spatial omics experiment to the biologically most

132
00:07:50.940 --> 00:07:52.440
important tissue area.

133
00:07:53.520 --> 00:07:57.500
And since the development of these methods, my lab has been continuing trying

134
00:07:57.520 --> 00:08:00.980
to push the field forward. Where our eventual goal is to turn

135
00:08:01.680 --> 00:08:05.540
histology slides into single cell resolution spatial maps at the

136
00:08:05.580 --> 00:08:06.260
population scale.

137
00:08:07.260 --> 00:08:11.200
But when predicting gene expression directly from histology images, we're

138
00:08:11.240 --> 00:08:14.940
facing a fundamental challenge. The challenge is that the gene expression is

139
00:08:15.080 --> 00:08:18.620
highly dynamic. The dynamic range can substantially vary from one

140
00:08:18.720 --> 00:08:22.640
person to the other. So when we directly predict a gene expression

141
00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:26.360
from histology images alone, we don't really know the relevant

142
00:08:26.440 --> 00:08:30.220
ranks of the dynamic ranges across the different people we are trying to

143
00:08:30.300 --> 00:08:34.201
predict. And this leads to two fundamental issues that we have to consider.

144
00:08:34.680 --> 00:08:38.350
The first issue is that when we do gene expression prediction at the population

145
00:08:38.461 --> 00:08:42.380
scale, we wanted to make sure that the predicted gene expression magnitudes are

146
00:08:42.400 --> 00:08:44.980
comparable across the different people we are predicting.

147
00:08:45.540 --> 00:08:49.440
But if you only have the histology images as input, this dynamic range

148
00:08:49.500 --> 00:08:53.340
is not available. The second risk is that when you only use

149
00:08:53.440 --> 00:08:57.400
the histology images as input, you are risking the possibility of generating

150
00:08:57.420 --> 00:08:59.280
a lot of false positive predictions.

151
00:08:59.709 --> 00:09:03.640
And this is an issue that none of the existing methods that are addressing or

152
00:09:03.700 --> 00:09:07.680
even talk about. But I think in order to apply these virtual predictions

153
00:09:07.860 --> 00:09:11.480
in the clinical applications, it's very important to ensure that we are

154
00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:15.140
reducing the false positive predictions from all of these AI

155
00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:19.180
models. So to solve this question, we asked, "What if

156
00:09:19.360 --> 00:09:23.320
we just provided the AI models a little bit of extra information, such

157
00:09:23.360 --> 00:09:27.320
that the AI knows the relevant ranks of the dynamic ranges that

158
00:09:27.340 --> 00:09:31.250
we are trying to predict?" It turns out bulk RNA-seq, which is

159
00:09:31.360 --> 00:09:35.160
very inexpensive to obtain, can exactly provide this information we need.

160
00:09:35.700 --> 00:09:39.640
And this motivated us to develop this AURORA model, where we

161
00:09:39.700 --> 00:09:43.640
utilize bulk RNA-seq data as a constraint for the AI models

162
00:09:44.020 --> 00:09:47.880
when doing the predictions. And in this process, we are trying to mimic

163
00:09:47.960 --> 00:09:50.780
how a human look at a histology slide.

164
00:09:51.280 --> 00:09:54.960
We gradually zoom into the tissue, and we progressively enhance the

165
00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:58.980
spatial resolution of the gene expression prediction we make until we reach

166
00:09:58.989 --> 00:10:00.860
to the final single cell resolution.

167
00:10:01.540 --> 00:10:05.400
And throughout this process, we also generate cell type predictions at

168
00:10:05.540 --> 00:10:09.340
every location we examine. So by the end of this analysis,

169
00:10:09.560 --> 00:10:13.520
we are able to give you a single cell resolution spatial map that has a single

170
00:10:13.580 --> 00:10:16.880
cell resolution spatial gene expression data across the whole transcriptome.

171
00:10:17.300 --> 00:10:21.220
And we are also able to give you the cell type information at every

172
00:10:21.280 --> 00:10:23.520
single location in the tissue of interest.

173
00:10:24.920 --> 00:10:27.660
So now let me show you some of the evaluations that we have.

174
00:10:28.239 --> 00:10:32.120
So in order to establish the reliability of AURORA, we need to

175
00:10:32.160 --> 00:10:35.000
compare the predicted values versus the ground truth.

176
00:10:35.560 --> 00:10:39.510
So in this analysis, we leverage the high quality spatial gene

177
00:10:39.540 --> 00:10:43.360
expression data generated by my wonderful collaborators, Dr.

178
00:10:43.400 --> 00:10:46.920
Houmam Akhdar and Lihua Wang's labs at MD Anderson.

179
00:10:47.500 --> 00:10:51.360
So in this dataset, we have utilized twenty-three

180
00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:55.400
lung adenocarcinoma patients, and we have the

181
00:10:55.460 --> 00:10:57.660
medium gene expression data generated from all of them.

182
00:10:58.260 --> 00:11:02.180
We spatially enhanced the resolution of this data into single cell level

183
00:11:02.220 --> 00:11:05.960
by iSTAR. And in this analysis, we trained our virtual

184
00:11:06.020 --> 00:11:09.560
prediction model using eighteen of the samples, and we virtually

185
00:11:09.640 --> 00:11:12.400
predicted the gene expression to the remaining five.

186
00:11:12.800 --> 00:11:16.660
And this allowed us to compare the predicted values and the

187
00:11:16.670 --> 00:11:19.420
directly measured values in the original experiment.

188
00:11:20.180 --> 00:11:24.060
And the lung tissue is particularly interesting, because in the lung tissue, there

189
00:11:24.080 --> 00:11:27.820
is a lot of airspace. If you see positive predictions in the

190
00:11:27.860 --> 00:11:31.800
airspace location, it means that you have false positive predictions.

191
00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:36.120
So this dataset allows us to evaluate not only the Pearson correlation

192
00:11:36.180 --> 00:11:39.880
between the predicted and the observed, but also allowed us to

193
00:11:39.940 --> 00:11:42.860
evaluate the degree of false positive predictions.

194
00:11:43.460 --> 00:11:47.420
So looking at the top right corner of the plot, you

195
00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:51.340
can see that among all of the methods that we compared to, AURORA

196
00:11:51.350 --> 00:11:54.770
achieved the highest Pearson correlation and the lowest false positive

197
00:11:54.820 --> 00:11:58.540
rate. In contrast, many of the state-of-the-art methods that are

198
00:11:58.660 --> 00:12:02.160
available out there, they generate false positive predictions.

199
00:12:02.660 --> 00:12:05.540
So now let me show you how a false positive prediction looks like.

200
00:12:06.110 --> 00:12:10.100
So in this tissue slide, you can see that we have a pathologist annotated blood

201
00:12:10.180 --> 00:12:13.840
vessels, and at the bottom left, you can see the ground truth

202
00:12:13.960 --> 00:12:17.888
measurement of gene MTH11.And if you compare the

203
00:12:17.908 --> 00:12:21.678
predictions of different approaches with the ground truth, you can see that

204
00:12:21.988 --> 00:12:25.868
AURORA achieved a high correlation and a very low false positive rate.

205
00:12:26.328 --> 00:12:30.168
In contrast, two of the top competing methods, they generated a lot of

206
00:12:30.188 --> 00:12:34.148
false positive signals. So this is just one of the many genes that we predicted.

207
00:12:34.448 --> 00:12:38.408
In reality, if you wanted to utilize these AI models in the clinical

208
00:12:38.468 --> 00:12:42.408
applications, you need to ensure that your predictions are reliable, you

209
00:12:42.448 --> 00:12:45.668
are not simply predicting false positives.

210
00:12:45.708 --> 00:12:49.328
So now after establishing the reliability of AURORA, we

211
00:12:49.368 --> 00:12:53.048
next applied AURORA to generate the single-cell resolution spatial

212
00:12:53.108 --> 00:12:56.038
maps on population cohort studies.

213
00:12:56.468 --> 00:13:00.268
And here we utilized the data produced by

214
00:13:00.308 --> 00:13:04.268
TCGA, and we virtually predicted a single-cell resolution spatial

215
00:13:04.328 --> 00:13:08.248
maps on nearly 4,000 TCGA samples across different tumor

216
00:13:08.268 --> 00:13:11.248
types. And in this talk, I'm going to focus on lung

217
00:13:11.328 --> 00:13:15.008
adenocarcinoma, and we applied our virtual prediction model

218
00:13:15.228 --> 00:13:16.888
trained on 18 medium samples

219
00:13:18.248 --> 00:13:22.068
to this TCGA cohort. So in total, we predicted

220
00:13:22.468 --> 00:13:25.888
885 TCGA lung adenocarcinoma slides.

221
00:13:26.348 --> 00:13:30.328
And at the bottom, you can see one of the tissue samples that we predicted.

222
00:13:31.008 --> 00:13:34.328
Although we don't really know the ground truth in TCGA, but we do know the

223
00:13:34.368 --> 00:13:38.288
underlying pathology. So if you look at the KRT8 expression

224
00:13:38.348 --> 00:13:42.148
that we predicted, you can see that the predicted expression pattern agreed

225
00:13:42.188 --> 00:13:44.648
very well with the known tumor pathology.

226
00:13:45.708 --> 00:13:49.668
So the real value of virtual prediction at the population scale lies

227
00:13:49.708 --> 00:13:53.468
in the possibility to identify important and clinically

228
00:13:53.568 --> 00:13:56.388
relevant spatial biomarkers for cancer.

229
00:13:56.968 --> 00:14:00.688
So to this end, we conducted a tumor spatial niche

230
00:14:00.848 --> 00:14:04.808
discovery. We utilized the cellular composition information

231
00:14:04.908 --> 00:14:08.328
we inferred from AURORA to do this tumor microenvironment

232
00:14:08.508 --> 00:14:12.108
analysis, and we identified quite a few interesting spatial

233
00:14:12.188 --> 00:14:15.408
biomarkers. So for example, we were able to detect

234
00:14:15.708 --> 00:14:19.148
TLS, which is well known to play an important role in antitumor

235
00:14:19.188 --> 00:14:22.768
response. And due to the high-resolution information we predict,

236
00:14:23.128 --> 00:14:27.048
we can also classify the TLS into early stage TLS

237
00:14:27.448 --> 00:14:31.368
and mature stage TLS. And we can further utilize the mature

238
00:14:31.408 --> 00:14:35.268
TLS that we identified to stratify the patients according to the areas of

239
00:14:35.348 --> 00:14:39.168
the mature TLS. And interestingly, we found that those patients

240
00:14:39.208 --> 00:14:43.028
that have a larger area of mature TLS, they tend to have

241
00:14:43.108 --> 00:14:44.528
a better survival.

242
00:14:45.368 --> 00:14:48.568
So after seeing this, we then asked a deeper question.

243
00:14:48.828 --> 00:14:50.868
We wanted to ask, does the location matter?

244
00:14:51.448 --> 00:14:55.308
So in this analysis, we looked at the co-localization between tumor

245
00:14:55.548 --> 00:14:59.468
and the TLS, and we found out that those patients that have higher

246
00:14:59.548 --> 00:15:03.538
degree of co-localization between tumor and the TLS, they tend to have

247
00:15:04.008 --> 00:15:07.948
better cancer survival. So this example demonstrated that

248
00:15:08.248 --> 00:15:12.048
by doing virtual predictions, we can even recover higher-order

249
00:15:12.268 --> 00:15:15.128
spatial structure in the tumor samples.

250
00:15:16.128 --> 00:15:20.068
And another interesting spatial biomarker we recovered in this

251
00:15:20.078 --> 00:15:22.388
analysis is what I call the spatial cuff.

252
00:15:22.788 --> 00:15:26.568
And in fact, this type of structure was first reported in the

253
00:15:26.578 --> 00:15:28.908
"Cancer Cell" paper by Dr. Linghua Wang's group.

254
00:15:29.488 --> 00:15:30.368
So in this paper,

255
00:15:31.648 --> 00:15:35.468
Dr. Linghua Wang's group conducted a very sophisticated interesting spatial

256
00:15:35.528 --> 00:15:39.288
analysis utilizing single-cell resolution spatial omics data

257
00:15:39.648 --> 00:15:43.328
generated from Xenium, CosMx, Merscope MC, and

258
00:15:43.468 --> 00:15:47.417
CODEX. And they discovered this structure called the

259
00:15:47.468 --> 00:15:51.368
Eisman cuff, where you can see that you have the tumor cells in the center, and

260
00:15:51.448 --> 00:15:55.288
they are surrounded by the cuffs. And this type of structure is conserved

261
00:15:55.348 --> 00:15:59.028
across different tumor types. And more importantly, this

262
00:15:59.088 --> 00:16:02.568
type of a spatial cuff leads to poor prognosis.

263
00:16:02.628 --> 00:16:06.448
So if you look at the top plot, you can see that using

264
00:16:06.508 --> 00:16:10.288
AURORA, we are able to recover and recapitulate this type of a

265
00:16:10.328 --> 00:16:14.228
spatial cuff pattern, and we further stratify our patients in the

266
00:16:14.268 --> 00:16:17.917
TCGA cohort according to how much this spatial cuff they

267
00:16:17.948 --> 00:16:21.917
possess. And we see that patients that have a higher degree of this

268
00:16:22.028 --> 00:16:25.928
spatial cuff tends to have a lower survival

269
00:16:26.168 --> 00:16:30.068
outcome. So this example demonstrated that those findings

270
00:16:30.088 --> 00:16:34.068
that you obtain from the expensive single-cell resolution spatial

271
00:16:34.107 --> 00:16:37.838
omics experiments can be recovered, recapitulated using this

272
00:16:38.028 --> 00:16:39.508
virtual prediction concept.

273
00:16:40.878 --> 00:16:44.617
So while transcriptomics is informative and powerful, but we know that

274
00:16:44.748 --> 00:16:48.708
biology is more than RNA. So in order to have a full picture of the tissue

275
00:16:48.728 --> 00:16:51.868
that we study, we need to understand the other omic

276
00:16:52.068 --> 00:16:55.808
modalities. So to solve this question, we recently developed a

277
00:16:55.848 --> 00:16:59.148
tool called MISL, which allowed us to simultaneously

278
00:16:59.508 --> 00:17:03.068
model multiple omic modalities together with histology image

279
00:17:03.168 --> 00:17:06.408
information for very high-resolution tissue segmentation.

280
00:17:07.068 --> 00:17:10.808
And using MISL, we were able to detect a very small structure called the

281
00:17:10.929 --> 00:17:14.108
high endothelial venule in the TLS automatically.

282
00:17:15.128 --> 00:17:16.388
Although MISL is powerful,

283
00:17:17.429 --> 00:17:20.998
currently it's only limited to the analysis of one single tissue

284
00:17:21.048 --> 00:17:24.768
section. But nowadays, in the real-world applications, we

285
00:17:24.848 --> 00:17:28.068
often see diverse spatial omics datasets

286
00:17:28.368 --> 00:17:32.148
generated from different tissue sections, either coming from the same patients

287
00:17:32.448 --> 00:17:36.288
or coming from diverse patients. And ideally, we wanted to

288
00:17:36.388 --> 00:17:40.288
have a technology that is able to simultaneously measure all

289
00:17:40.348 --> 00:17:43.148
of the potential omic modalities on the same tissue size.

290
00:17:43.568 --> 00:17:47.348
But realistically, this is almost impossible because as you're adding

291
00:17:47.388 --> 00:17:51.348
additional omic modalities onto the same tissue size, you cannot avoid to

292
00:17:51.428 --> 00:17:55.398
destroy the sample, meaning that the quality of the data you'll get is

293
00:17:55.448 --> 00:17:59.348
going to be degraded. So in order to solve this challenge, we

294
00:17:59.388 --> 00:18:03.338
recently developed another tool called Old Cozy, which allows us

295
00:18:03.368 --> 00:18:06.908
to use a sophisticated graph-based approach to integrate

296
00:18:06.928 --> 00:18:10.698
fragmented spatial omics data to virtually reconstruct what I

297
00:18:10.768 --> 00:18:14.728
call the complete spatial omics. So the goal is that by the end

298
00:18:14.768 --> 00:18:18.728
of this integration, we can do this virtual prediction and virtually predict

299
00:18:18.988 --> 00:18:22.908
missing omic modalities, meaning that we can turn a task that

300
00:18:22.968 --> 00:18:26.448
is experimentally impossible into something that is computationally

301
00:18:26.528 --> 00:18:30.488
feasibleSo to demonstrate the power of COZEE, let me show

302
00:18:30.508 --> 00:18:33.988
you an application again to this lung cancer study.

303
00:18:34.588 --> 00:18:37.628
So in this analysis, we virtually integrated

304
00:18:38.928 --> 00:18:42.488
three million cells obtained from four lung

305
00:18:42.548 --> 00:18:46.248
adenocarcinoma patients. And you can see that the first two patients,

306
00:18:46.528 --> 00:18:48.248
they have a histology image measure.

307
00:18:48.448 --> 00:18:50.918
They also have a whole transcriptomic gene expression.

308
00:18:51.468 --> 00:18:54.878
And the third patient has a histology image and the proteins.

309
00:18:55.348 --> 00:18:59.028
And the fourth patient only has a histology image information available.

310
00:18:59.648 --> 00:19:03.308
And by doing this integration and computational virtual

311
00:19:03.348 --> 00:19:07.308
prediction, we are able to identify a small cluster

312
00:19:07.548 --> 00:19:09.178
that is corresponding to macrophages.

313
00:19:09.638 --> 00:19:12.978
And the reason that we are able to infer that this cluster is corresponding to

314
00:19:13.008 --> 00:19:16.738
macrophages is because we're able to leverage the molecular information

315
00:19:16.748 --> 00:19:20.468
provided by the previous three samples.

316
00:19:20.478 --> 00:19:24.218
So after we identified the macrophages on patient four using their

317
00:19:24.368 --> 00:19:28.068
HE as input only, we visualized our results

318
00:19:28.128 --> 00:19:32.028
together with our pathologist collaborator, and the pathologist confirmed

319
00:19:32.127 --> 00:19:35.948
that the cluster we identified in patient four indeed

320
00:19:35.988 --> 00:19:37.488
corresponding to macrophages.

321
00:19:38.648 --> 00:19:41.008
So here are the virtual predictions we produced.

322
00:19:41.368 --> 00:19:45.228
You can see that our virtually predicted spatial gene expression profiles and the

323
00:19:45.288 --> 00:19:49.048
protein expression profiles agreed with the direct measurements very

324
00:19:49.068 --> 00:19:49.288
well.

325
00:19:50.548 --> 00:19:54.128
And using COZEE, we can further integrate data in the 3D context.

326
00:19:54.568 --> 00:19:58.328
So suppose you have zero tissue sections generated from a

327
00:19:58.468 --> 00:20:02.388
3D tumor block, but in reality, it's very possible that you use different

328
00:20:02.588 --> 00:20:05.588
spatial omics technologies using different tissue sections.

329
00:20:05.988 --> 00:20:09.628
So using COZEE, we're able to integrate everything together into the same space.

330
00:20:10.038 --> 00:20:13.528
And now you can visualize the multi-omic information in the real

331
00:20:13.688 --> 00:20:17.518
3D tumor volume, and you can see some structures that

332
00:20:17.588 --> 00:20:20.768
cannot be seen while you study the tissue sections in 2D.

333
00:20:21.248 --> 00:20:24.808
So, for example, we were able to visualize the complex

334
00:20:24.948 --> 00:20:28.648
TIAs network, and in addition, you can study the

335
00:20:28.708 --> 00:20:31.488
spatial relationship between blood vessels and the

336
00:20:31.508 --> 00:20:35.068
tumor. And in this analysis, in fact, we did

337
00:20:35.368 --> 00:20:37.808
very, very comprehensive evaluations.

338
00:20:38.068 --> 00:20:41.737
We considered almost all of the possible omic modalities, ranging from

339
00:20:41.768 --> 00:20:45.678
histone modifications to chromatin accessibility, gene expression,

340
00:20:45.788 --> 00:20:47.728
and protein abundance, and metabolites.

341
00:20:48.268 --> 00:20:51.998
And we also considered almost all of the possible existing commercialized

342
00:20:52.148 --> 00:20:56.028
spatial omics platforms out there, and we also considered many different

343
00:20:56.068 --> 00:20:58.908
tissue types and disease contexts.

344
00:20:58.968 --> 00:21:02.668
If you want to learn more about COZEE, you are welcome to read our recent archive

345
00:21:02.708 --> 00:21:03.028
paper.

346
00:21:04.208 --> 00:21:07.868
So to scale up this biological insight to the

347
00:21:07.908 --> 00:21:11.828
broader field, we recently developed the Foundation model.

348
00:21:12.248 --> 00:21:15.408
So here, we utilized the rich dataset produced by Dr.

349
00:21:15.588 --> 00:21:19.508
Kadaris and Dr. Wong's labs. And we build our

350
00:21:19.608 --> 00:21:23.168
Foundation model using 36 million cells

351
00:21:23.588 --> 00:21:26.968
generated from 54 tissue sections.

352
00:21:27.028 --> 00:21:30.368
And in this dataset, we have a rich spatial

353
00:21:30.588 --> 00:21:34.328
annotation information obtained by the pathologist, and we also

354
00:21:34.388 --> 00:21:36.288
have whole transcriptomic gene expression data.

355
00:21:36.688 --> 00:21:40.348
We also have protein expression data across 35 proteins.

356
00:21:40.908 --> 00:21:44.768
So by building this Foundation model, now the research community can simply

357
00:21:44.828 --> 00:21:48.288
fit in your data into our Foundation model, and we are able to give you

358
00:21:48.408 --> 00:21:51.708
comprehensive multi-modal information at a single-cell resolution.

359
00:21:52.248 --> 00:21:54.408
We're able to give you the pathologist annotation.

360
00:21:54.728 --> 00:21:57.348
We're able to give you the whole transcriptomic gene expression information.

361
00:21:57.668 --> 00:22:01.388
We're able to give you the whole 35 protein spatial

362
00:22:01.398 --> 00:22:04.978
proteomics information, all at the single-cell resolution level.

363
00:22:05.768 --> 00:22:09.508
So now let me show you the application to the TCCCA cohort using COZEE

364
00:22:09.528 --> 00:22:13.508
Foundation. So you can see that by applying the histology images

365
00:22:13.588 --> 00:22:16.968
in the TCCCA cohort into COZEE Foundation, we're now able to

366
00:22:17.008 --> 00:22:20.898
transfer the pathologist annotation in our training

367
00:22:20.968 --> 00:22:24.408
dataset onto TCCCA. So now we have the annotation available.

368
00:22:24.828 --> 00:22:27.828
Additionally, we are able to produce a whole transcript from spatial gene

369
00:22:27.888 --> 00:22:31.388
expression and the protein expression for 35 proteins at a single-cell

370
00:22:31.408 --> 00:22:35.328
resolution. And because the resolution is so high, this allows us

371
00:22:35.348 --> 00:22:37.598
to automatically detect the tumor boundary.

372
00:22:38.048 --> 00:22:40.868
So here are four representative samples in the TCCCA.

373
00:22:41.348 --> 00:22:45.088
You can see that the boundary we detected is very fine-grained, and this

374
00:22:45.188 --> 00:22:49.108
analysis is very fast. Imagine if you ask a pathologist to manually annotate the

375
00:22:49.128 --> 00:22:52.348
tumor boundary in the TCCCA cohort, how long that is going to take.

376
00:22:52.657 --> 00:22:55.448
And this analysis is totally unsupervised. It's super fast.

377
00:22:56.088 --> 00:22:59.848
And this tumor boundary analysis further allowed us to conduct a tumor

378
00:22:59.968 --> 00:23:03.428
interface analysis. So, for example, we can look at the cell type

379
00:23:03.508 --> 00:23:07.468
compositions along the tumor edge, and we found that

380
00:23:07.748 --> 00:23:11.668
those samples that have a higher proportion of lymphocytes along the tumor

381
00:23:11.788 --> 00:23:13.628
edge, they tend to have a better survival.

382
00:23:14.248 --> 00:23:17.668
And furthermore, we conducted this spatial gradient analysis.

383
00:23:18.208 --> 00:23:22.148
We looked from the tumor edge into the tumor core, and we gradually

384
00:23:22.188 --> 00:23:26.008
examined the proportions of lymphocytes from the tumor edge

385
00:23:26.288 --> 00:23:29.998
down to the tumor core. And this allowed us to examine which patients

386
00:23:30.148 --> 00:23:34.108
have a higher degree of lymphocyte infiltration as compared to the

387
00:23:34.168 --> 00:23:38.028
other. And interestingly, we found out that those patients that have a

388
00:23:38.108 --> 00:23:41.888
higher degree of lymphocyte infiltration into the tumor core,

389
00:23:42.288 --> 00:23:44.208
they tend to have a better cancer survival.

390
00:23:45.548 --> 00:23:49.348
So, so far I have demonstrated that virtual predictions can

391
00:23:49.428 --> 00:23:53.408
help us produce a population scale spatial omics datasets,

392
00:23:53.768 --> 00:23:57.748
and this can allow us to automatically detect the tumor boundary, tumor edge,

393
00:23:58.148 --> 00:24:02.088
tumor interface, et cetera, and can help us identify potential

394
00:24:02.128 --> 00:24:05.768
spatial biomarkers. But in order to utilize these virtual prediction

395
00:24:05.868 --> 00:24:09.728
tools in the clinical setting, we wanted to make sure that the results we

396
00:24:09.748 --> 00:24:13.708
produce are reliable. And the clinicians need to know where the model is certain,

397
00:24:14.128 --> 00:24:15.768
where the model is just simply guessing.

398
00:24:16.808 --> 00:24:20.518
So in order to address this real challenge, we developed another

399
00:24:20.548 --> 00:24:24.328
tool called Utopia, where we wanted to use principle statistical

400
00:24:24.368 --> 00:24:28.338
approaches to help people understand why we are

401
00:24:28.368 --> 00:24:32.164
confident about our virtual predictionsSo Utopia is

402
00:24:32.304 --> 00:24:35.964
based on a statistical technique called conformal learning, which means that

403
00:24:36.144 --> 00:24:39.444
our model, our approach, is a prediction model

404
00:24:39.524 --> 00:24:43.384
agnostic, meaning that this approach can be applied

405
00:24:43.484 --> 00:24:45.824
to any virtual prediction models.

406
00:24:46.404 --> 00:24:50.284
And using Utopia, we can give you a statistically calibrated

407
00:24:50.404 --> 00:24:51.204
confidence score

408
00:24:52.904 --> 00:24:56.704
depending on the spatial resolution you are considering and depending on the

409
00:24:57.104 --> 00:24:58.824
biological target you are predicting.

410
00:24:59.224 --> 00:25:03.044
So here we consider the different spatial resolutions ranging from lower

411
00:25:03.124 --> 00:25:07.024
resolution to higher single-cell resolution, and we also consider the

412
00:25:07.044 --> 00:25:10.644
different biological entities that we predict, ranging from a single

413
00:25:10.664 --> 00:25:14.194
gene to a meta-gene, from by the combination of multiple genes,

414
00:25:14.544 --> 00:25:18.384
and from a specific cell type to a more broadly defined cell class.

415
00:25:19.124 --> 00:25:21.544
So here I want to show you a real-world application.

416
00:25:21.964 --> 00:25:25.934
So in this analysis, we focused on the virtual prediction problem in

417
00:25:26.084 --> 00:25:29.924
a sample that has gastric cancer. We built our

418
00:25:29.964 --> 00:25:33.884
virtual prediction model using the molecular information obtained from

419
00:25:33.944 --> 00:25:37.444
the two red boxes, the regions of interest we selected.

420
00:25:37.984 --> 00:25:41.684
And after we built our virtual prediction model, we applied this virtual prediction

421
00:25:41.744 --> 00:25:45.664
model to the rest of the tissue, only using the underlying historic image

422
00:25:45.704 --> 00:25:49.624
information as input. So now you can see that across

423
00:25:49.724 --> 00:25:53.484
the different spatial resolutions that we predict, lower resolutions are

424
00:25:53.544 --> 00:25:54.184
much easier

425
00:25:55.284 --> 00:25:58.414
to obtain a higher confidence than a higher resolution.

426
00:25:58.584 --> 00:26:02.464
This makes a lot of sense. And we also see that predicting a single gene like

427
00:26:02.484 --> 00:26:06.164
CD4 is a much harder task than predicting a meta-gene like a

428
00:26:06.184 --> 00:26:10.104
TIS signature. And we also found that a continuous variable,

429
00:26:10.204 --> 00:26:14.024
so the gene expression, is much harder to predict than a categorical

430
00:26:14.044 --> 00:26:17.424
variable like a cell type. So basically, by doing this

431
00:26:17.434 --> 00:26:21.204
analysis, we are able to give you a principle, a statistical

432
00:26:21.324 --> 00:26:25.044
framework that can tell you where your virtual predictions are reliable,

433
00:26:25.284 --> 00:26:27.004
where your virtual predictions are not reliable.

434
00:26:27.464 --> 00:26:30.974
So this means that when we utilize virtual predictions in the clinical setting,

435
00:26:31.504 --> 00:26:35.324
we know where is the tissue region that we should conduct

436
00:26:35.334 --> 00:26:37.484
the real spatial omics experiment.

437
00:26:38.184 --> 00:26:41.994
So to summarize, spatial omics is a powerful technology, but

438
00:26:42.124 --> 00:26:45.904
currently, spatial omics is still too expensive to scale up in the

439
00:26:45.944 --> 00:26:49.624
real-world applications. And in this talk, I have demonstrated

440
00:26:50.044 --> 00:26:53.904
to you that by using innovative AI tools, we can now

441
00:26:54.044 --> 00:26:57.984
turn histopathology data into digital tissue twins, where

442
00:26:58.064 --> 00:27:01.504
every H&amp;E slide can now become a spatially

443
00:27:01.564 --> 00:27:04.344
resolved and molecularly informed tissue map.

444
00:27:04.894 --> 00:27:08.344
And this allows us to scale spatial omics across

445
00:27:08.384 --> 00:27:12.184
diverse patient populations, and the resulting data will enable

446
00:27:12.304 --> 00:27:16.184
us to do risk prediction, patient stratification, and also allows

447
00:27:16.224 --> 00:27:19.434
us to bridge spatial biology, AI, and

448
00:27:19.464 --> 00:27:21.644
therapeutic decision making together.

449
00:27:22.564 --> 00:27:26.404
So before I finish, I wanted to thank the following members of my lab

450
00:27:26.704 --> 00:27:28.844
who did much of the work I presented today.

451
00:27:29.284 --> 00:27:32.764
I also wanted to thank my wonderful collaborators and my funding support.

452
00:27:32.974 --> 00:27:34.363
Thank you very much for your attention.

453
00:27:38.104 --> 00:27:39.654
Happy to take questions. Yeah.

454
00:27:39.784 --> 00:27:40.624
Please, questions at the end.

455
00:27:40.684 --> 00:27:40.844
Okay.

456
00:27:42.424 --> 00:27:42.884
Yeah.

457
00:27:42.904 --> 00:27:44.224
Thank you.

458
00:27:46.664 --> 00:27:49.204
Thank you so much for this amazing talk.

459
00:27:49.524 --> 00:27:52.764
And could you please put on the James Xu's

460
00:27:52.904 --> 00:27:54.264
recording? Thank you.

461
00:28:13.924 --> 00:28:17.644
Hi, everyone. I apologize that I'm not able to attend AACR in

462
00:28:17.714 --> 00:28:19.784
person this year, but I'm happy to

463
00:28:21.224 --> 00:28:24.364
present some of the work we've been doing around generative and agentic

464
00:28:24.444 --> 00:28:26.564
AI for spatial omics.

465
00:28:29.884 --> 00:28:31.534
So this presentation will have two parts.

466
00:28:31.704 --> 00:28:35.644
In the first part, I want to present this AI method that we developed called

467
00:28:35.684 --> 00:28:39.144
Rosie, which is an approach to generate in

468
00:28:39.204 --> 00:28:42.564
silico spatial proteomic images from H&amp;E.

469
00:28:43.324 --> 00:28:47.224
In the second part, I want to explore some of the applications in using these

470
00:28:47.263 --> 00:28:51.184
kind of spatial and other single-cell omics data to

471
00:28:51.244 --> 00:28:53.464
accelerate therapeutic development.

472
00:28:53.914 --> 00:28:57.184
And we'll do this with AI agents, with the virtual biotech.

473
00:29:01.084 --> 00:29:04.014
So there's been tremendous interest in generating very rich

474
00:29:05.124 --> 00:29:08.104
spatial omics information from tissue samples,

475
00:29:09.044 --> 00:29:09.464
and

476
00:29:10.564 --> 00:29:14.084
spatial proteomics that leverages multiplex

477
00:29:14.124 --> 00:29:18.104
immunofluorescence imaging has emerged as a particularly promising

478
00:29:18.114 --> 00:29:21.924
approach. So methods like Codex can simultaneously

479
00:29:21.964 --> 00:29:25.444
image 50 to 100 different protein markers in

480
00:29:25.484 --> 00:29:28.044
parallel on the same tissue sections.

481
00:29:28.754 --> 00:29:32.684
And this enables us then to be able to phenotype many more different cell types

482
00:29:32.724 --> 00:29:36.684
at higher resolution, and also be able to understand some of

483
00:29:36.724 --> 00:29:40.344
the better tumor microenvironments and cell-cell interactions.

484
00:29:43.944 --> 00:29:47.584
However, generating such high dimensional single-cell

485
00:29:47.604 --> 00:29:50.904
spatial omics data is quite

486
00:29:51.164 --> 00:29:55.124
expensive, right? So here's sort of a comparison across different

487
00:29:55.164 --> 00:29:59.124
methods. So with H&amp;E images, the molecular information we collect is

488
00:29:59.244 --> 00:30:03.204
relatively sparse. It's mostly capturing morphologies, but the benefit

489
00:30:03.244 --> 00:30:04.044
is that it's very

490
00:30:05.004 --> 00:30:07.444
cheap and also can be collected in a few hours.

491
00:30:08.604 --> 00:30:12.244
However, if we move towards this highly multiplexed immunofluorescence

492
00:30:12.324 --> 00:30:15.804
imaging like Codex, which is now able to capture at

493
00:30:15.864 --> 00:30:19.484
single-cell resolution, 50 plus different biomarkers,

494
00:30:20.124 --> 00:30:23.804
but the cost is much more expensive, can be thousands of dollars per

495
00:30:23.924 --> 00:30:26.664
slide and also takes multiple days to collect.

496
00:30:27.124 --> 00:30:30.944
So there's this really several orders of magnitude increase in cost and

497
00:30:31.004 --> 00:30:34.924
complexity when we go from H&amp;E to this highly multiplexed

498
00:30:35.204 --> 00:30:39.164
spatial proteomics.So our goal here

499
00:30:39.284 --> 00:30:40.984
is to see, can we actually use

500
00:30:42.064 --> 00:30:45.584
this H&amp;E kind of images to help us to generate in

501
00:30:45.644 --> 00:30:48.324
silico CODEX, in silico spatial omics?

502
00:30:49.304 --> 00:30:53.064
And this is analogous in some ways to the ability of AI to try to

503
00:30:53.424 --> 00:30:56.864
colorize black and white images into these more vivid

504
00:30:56.964 --> 00:31:00.904
colors. Right, so in our case, we view the H&amp;E image as sort

505
00:31:00.924 --> 00:31:04.864
of analogous to these black and white images, and we

506
00:31:04.904 --> 00:31:08.704
want to essentially use AI to add these different colors to it so that it looks

507
00:31:08.724 --> 00:31:12.244
more like this very rich kind of spatial omics, like a

508
00:31:12.424 --> 00:31:13.164
CODEX data.

509
00:31:15.884 --> 00:31:19.684
In order to do this, we need to build a trainer model that can impute

510
00:31:22.664 --> 00:31:23.204
CODEX

511
00:31:24.564 --> 00:31:28.104
proteomics data from H&amp;E images. And this

512
00:31:28.144 --> 00:31:31.884
requires collecting a large paired data set where we have both H&amp;E

513
00:31:31.944 --> 00:31:35.824
images and CODEX measurements that are measured on the exact same tissue

514
00:31:35.904 --> 00:31:36.424
sections.

515
00:31:37.524 --> 00:31:41.484
So to do this, we collaborated with our collaborators at

516
00:31:41.544 --> 00:31:45.504
Enable Medicine, and we generated, at the time, the largest paired H&amp;E

517
00:31:45.604 --> 00:31:49.524
and CODEX data sets. So this is the data set we collected for ROSI,

518
00:31:49.644 --> 00:31:53.404
which has over 2,000 samples covering 30 million

519
00:31:53.504 --> 00:31:55.804
cells from 16 different disease types.

520
00:31:56.534 --> 00:32:00.424
And this is all done at sort of a high resolution at the individual pixel level.

521
00:32:01.164 --> 00:32:05.084
And importantly here, the CODEX and H&amp;E images are coming from the same tissue,

522
00:32:05.164 --> 00:32:08.684
so they're perfectly aligned. And this is orders of magnitude

523
00:32:08.724 --> 00:32:12.584
larger than the data sets that we used in previous work from our

524
00:32:12.644 --> 00:32:14.164
group, where we were able to

525
00:32:15.264 --> 00:32:18.764
also do some of these imputations, but it was done on a much more limited set.

526
00:32:22.364 --> 00:32:23.434
So leveraging this

527
00:32:24.424 --> 00:32:25.704
large scale paired data set,

528
00:32:26.524 --> 00:32:30.124
we developed ROSI, and here's sort of a brief overview of how it works.

529
00:32:30.904 --> 00:32:34.724
So it takes input, the standard H&amp;E images, and the

530
00:32:34.764 --> 00:32:36.304
algorithm will first

531
00:32:38.404 --> 00:32:40.704
crop those images into these individual patches.

532
00:32:40.784 --> 00:32:43.604
Each patch will be 128 by 128 pixels.

533
00:32:44.504 --> 00:32:47.683
And then we have a deep learning model that takes that patch, right, and then try

534
00:32:47.724 --> 00:32:51.384
to predict and to impute the proteomics

535
00:32:51.444 --> 00:32:55.044
profiles for each of these 50 or more biomarkers

536
00:32:55.624 --> 00:32:58.704
at a much smaller, higher resolution of eight by eight

537
00:32:58.804 --> 00:33:02.494
pixels. And the benefit of doing this is that this

538
00:33:02.524 --> 00:33:06.044
enables the model to be able to capture information from a broader,

539
00:33:06.184 --> 00:33:09.644
larger context in order to predict and impute the

540
00:33:09.964 --> 00:33:13.904
biomarkers at a smaller window. And we showed in our paper that this

541
00:33:13.944 --> 00:33:15.924
is a more effective approach.

542
00:33:16.744 --> 00:33:20.604
And after that imputation, then the algorithm would take these

543
00:33:20.704 --> 00:33:24.124
imputed eight by eight patches and stitch them all back

544
00:33:24.204 --> 00:33:26.484
together into this whole slide level,

545
00:33:27.404 --> 00:33:29.864
generated spatial proteomic image.

546
00:33:29.944 --> 00:33:33.484
That's the in silico CODEX output from the ROSI

547
00:33:33.544 --> 00:33:36.884
algorithm. This in silico CODEX then will be perfectly

548
00:33:36.924 --> 00:33:39.464
aligned with the original H&amp;E sample.

549
00:33:41.844 --> 00:33:45.444
So with this approach, ROSI is able to predict in

550
00:33:45.664 --> 00:33:49.164
silico CODEX for up to 50 different biomarkers.

551
00:33:49.744 --> 00:33:53.724
So here's an example demonstration where we have these two H&amp;E images

552
00:33:53.744 --> 00:33:55.604
that were given as input into the algorithm.

553
00:33:56.204 --> 00:33:59.224
And in the second column, I show the generated

554
00:34:00.424 --> 00:34:03.084
in silico data that's imputed

555
00:34:03.944 --> 00:34:07.304
by ROSI algorithm. And this can take maybe

556
00:34:08.424 --> 00:34:09.225
less than $1,

557
00:34:10.464 --> 00:34:13.234
less than an hour of time. A few minutes.

558
00:34:14.044 --> 00:34:17.834
And the third column corresponds to where we took multiple days and

559
00:34:17.904 --> 00:34:21.864
thousands of dollars to perform the actual experiment to do this CODEX

560
00:34:21.904 --> 00:34:23.705
multiplex immunofluorescent imaging.

561
00:34:24.584 --> 00:34:28.265
And comparing the ROSI output with the experimental outcome, which is the ground

562
00:34:28.364 --> 00:34:32.225
truth, we can see that the ROSI output actually captures a lot of the

563
00:34:32.544 --> 00:34:36.124
key structures and cell types as you do from the actual

564
00:34:36.165 --> 00:34:40.004
experiments. And this is orders of magnitude, I think,

565
00:34:40.084 --> 00:34:42.084
over 1,000 times faster and cheaper.

566
00:34:45.084 --> 00:34:48.245
And in order to show that the results are quite representative across different

567
00:34:48.364 --> 00:34:51.394
samples, what I'm showing here is actually the different

568
00:34:51.504 --> 00:34:53.745
percentiles of different input

569
00:34:54.644 --> 00:34:58.424
histology H&amp;E images, where we rank

570
00:34:58.544 --> 00:35:02.404
these different images by the Pearson correlation between

571
00:35:02.484 --> 00:35:03.644
their imputed

572
00:35:05.104 --> 00:35:07.604
CODEX with the actual experimentally measured CODEX.

573
00:35:08.224 --> 00:35:11.624
So 99th percentile corresponds to the samples where the ROSI performed

574
00:35:11.664 --> 00:35:15.184
better, and the 25th percentile corresponds to samples where our

575
00:35:15.224 --> 00:35:17.144
algorithm performed relatively worse.

576
00:35:18.164 --> 00:35:21.734
And what we can see here is that even if we look at the medium sample or the 25th

577
00:35:21.784 --> 00:35:25.324
sample where the algorithm performed relatively worse, the output

578
00:35:25.624 --> 00:35:29.444
from the in silico CODEX actually still matches a lot of the fine grain

579
00:35:29.524 --> 00:35:33.164
structures that you see from the actual spatial CODEX measurements.

580
00:35:33.944 --> 00:35:37.444
So this gives us more confidence that the algorithm can be quite

581
00:35:37.504 --> 00:35:40.824
reliable. We also perform additional assessments

582
00:35:40.924 --> 00:35:44.804
on data on H&amp;E images from other locations.

583
00:35:44.844 --> 00:35:48.684
So here are data from three different external sites, and here the ROSI algorithm

584
00:35:48.804 --> 00:35:52.524
is also able to impute and generate some of these fine grain

585
00:35:52.584 --> 00:35:56.404
structures that we saw in these out-of-distribution external validation

586
00:35:56.444 --> 00:35:56.824
sites.

587
00:36:02.184 --> 00:36:05.844
And one benefit and one application of this approach was in silico

588
00:36:05.904 --> 00:36:06.824
CODEX of ROSI,

589
00:36:07.644 --> 00:36:11.064
is that we can actually then infer more granular tissue

590
00:36:11.164 --> 00:36:13.524
structures directly from the H&amp;E images.

591
00:36:14.664 --> 00:36:17.604
So here we're looking at three common kinds of tissue structures.

592
00:36:17.704 --> 00:36:21.344
So in dark blue, it's the stroma, light blue is the more

593
00:36:21.444 --> 00:36:25.224
tumor-like epithelium, and orange captures these more endothelium

594
00:36:25.304 --> 00:36:25.904
structures.

595
00:36:27.044 --> 00:36:30.964
And on the first column are the ground truth that we get from

596
00:36:31.084 --> 00:36:34.344
when we actually do the expensive spatial proteomics

597
00:36:34.404 --> 00:36:38.184
experimental measurements. We can capture these structures

598
00:36:38.224 --> 00:36:41.988
very accurately.And the second column corresponds to if we use

599
00:36:42.228 --> 00:36:46.048
Rosie to first impute the spatial proteomics and then do the

600
00:36:46.108 --> 00:36:50.068
same kind of segmentations. We can see here we often capture very similar,

601
00:36:50.328 --> 00:36:53.948
very precise imputed structures compared to the ground truth.

602
00:36:54.988 --> 00:36:58.608
We also did a comparison where we took the original H&amp;E image itself

603
00:36:59.108 --> 00:37:02.888
and extract morphology features from the H&amp;E image, and then trained

604
00:37:03.368 --> 00:37:07.148
a deep learning model to directly predict these structures from the

605
00:37:07.308 --> 00:37:10.968
H&amp;E image morphologies, and that actually performed much worse.

606
00:37:11.668 --> 00:37:15.588
So I think this is kind of an interesting comparison that demonstrates the benefit

607
00:37:15.648 --> 00:37:19.608
of this Rosie approach to first impute the high

608
00:37:19.848 --> 00:37:23.768
multiplex proteomics structures and then use those proteomics information then

609
00:37:23.828 --> 00:37:26.828
to classify the different tissue structures.

610
00:37:27.408 --> 00:37:31.088
So that ends up being richer and more robust than directly trying to

611
00:37:31.968 --> 00:37:34.578
classify the tissue structures from

612
00:37:34.668 --> 00:37:37.828
the morphology information itself.

613
00:37:40.848 --> 00:37:44.328
And then finally, one of the benefits of Rosie is that it's really able to make

614
00:37:44.368 --> 00:37:48.268
these imputations at a single pixel resolution,

615
00:37:48.308 --> 00:37:51.308
which corresponds to around 25 microns.

616
00:37:52.328 --> 00:37:55.608
So this enables the algorithm then to capture a lot of the

617
00:37:55.768 --> 00:37:57.368
sub-single-cell resolution,

618
00:37:58.408 --> 00:38:01.088
spatial structures of different proteins.

619
00:38:01.628 --> 00:38:05.028
So this enables richer kinds of sub-single-cell or subcellular

620
00:38:05.088 --> 00:38:05.768
analysis.

621
00:38:07.878 --> 00:38:11.808
So just to summarize, so with Rosie, we demonstrate

622
00:38:12.088 --> 00:38:15.728
that from H&amp;E images, we can actually use AI to

623
00:38:15.788 --> 00:38:19.598
infer protein expressions, cell types, structures

624
00:38:20.148 --> 00:38:23.888
that typically required much more expensive multiplex

625
00:38:23.968 --> 00:38:25.608
immunofluorescent imaging assays.

626
00:38:26.408 --> 00:38:30.328
And this demonstrates the power and the promise of AI to help

627
00:38:30.388 --> 00:38:34.128
us to bridge the gap between these more common and routinely available

628
00:38:34.228 --> 00:38:37.808
assays and these much more experimental research-level

629
00:38:37.888 --> 00:38:41.508
assays. And all of this can help us to enable

630
00:38:41.528 --> 00:38:42.748
precision pathology.

631
00:38:45.768 --> 00:38:49.688
So with Rosie, we see how with these kind of generative AI approaches, we can

632
00:38:50.128 --> 00:38:54.068
enable us to make these spatial omics information more broadly

633
00:38:54.108 --> 00:38:58.028
accessible by imputing them from H&amp;E images.

634
00:38:58.948 --> 00:39:02.768
In the second part, I want to highlight some examples of how we can then take

635
00:39:02.808 --> 00:39:06.708
these kinds of single-cell and spatial omics assays and help us

636
00:39:06.748 --> 00:39:08.088
with therapeutic developments.

637
00:39:09.328 --> 00:39:13.268
In a recent work, we created what we call a virtual biotech,

638
00:39:13.808 --> 00:39:17.788
which is a large organization of different AI agents that can help us with

639
00:39:17.848 --> 00:39:19.288
drug discovery and development.

640
00:39:20.228 --> 00:39:24.098
In this virtual biotech, it's a team of tens of thousands of AI agents,

641
00:39:24.408 --> 00:39:28.198
which is led by a chief scientist officer, or CSO agent, and

642
00:39:28.228 --> 00:39:31.848
working under the CSO agent, we have these different divisions, which

643
00:39:31.857 --> 00:39:35.768
corresponds to the standard cross-functional divisions of a

644
00:39:35.808 --> 00:39:38.547
typical drug discovery organization.

645
00:39:38.588 --> 00:39:41.988
So, for example, we have a division of agents that focuses on target

646
00:39:42.008 --> 00:39:45.508
identification, another division of agents that look at safety,

647
00:39:45.948 --> 00:39:47.428
clinical developments, and so on.

648
00:39:48.048 --> 00:39:51.668
All of these divisions are operationalized by teams of AI agents

649
00:39:52.108 --> 00:39:54.288
with different specializations for

650
00:39:55.688 --> 00:39:59.408
specialized roles. For example, under the target ID division, we

651
00:39:59.468 --> 00:40:03.088
actually have an AI agent who specializes in doing single-cell

652
00:40:03.148 --> 00:40:06.908
analysis, another agent that's very good at doing all the statistical genetics

653
00:40:06.988 --> 00:40:10.668
analysis, and also agents that specialize in doing these more spatial

654
00:40:11.688 --> 00:40:12.388
analysis.

655
00:40:14.248 --> 00:40:17.528
And behind the scenes, to enable these agents to

656
00:40:18.088 --> 00:40:21.488
carry this very in-depth analysis, we created a

657
00:40:21.548 --> 00:40:25.488
universe of different resources and tools that enables

658
00:40:25.588 --> 00:40:28.848
agents then to do analysis from the raw data.

659
00:40:28.908 --> 00:40:32.048
So this corresponds to hundreds of different MCPs that we've collected.

660
00:40:32.848 --> 00:40:36.648
So, for example, we have created MCP so that enables the agents to

661
00:40:36.708 --> 00:40:40.408
directly access and download single-cell atlas data that are

662
00:40:40.448 --> 00:40:44.148
relevant for their analysis. They can also access all of these different histology

663
00:40:44.268 --> 00:40:45.137
H&amp;E images

664
00:40:46.308 --> 00:40:50.148
as well as data from genetics, from clinical trials, and from chemistry.

665
00:40:51.948 --> 00:40:55.268
And the way that all of this work together is that

666
00:40:55.888 --> 00:40:59.568
the user might have a specific query, and the query could be,

667
00:40:59.598 --> 00:41:03.388
"Help me develop a therapeutic strategy for a particular kind

668
00:41:03.488 --> 00:41:07.108
of disease target," for example. And then the CSO agent

669
00:41:07.528 --> 00:41:11.428
would take that query and work with his chief of staff to come up with

670
00:41:11.508 --> 00:41:15.438
a plan for the analysis. And then it would delegate that plan to the

671
00:41:15.468 --> 00:41:19.308
different divisions of agents. All these agents then would proceed

672
00:41:19.348 --> 00:41:22.808
in parallel. Maybe one agent will look at the histology images, another agent will

673
00:41:22.848 --> 00:41:26.808
look at the genetics data. They can do all of these analysis in parallel.

674
00:41:26.828 --> 00:41:30.008
We have a reviewer agent that reviews all of these intermediate results.

675
00:41:30.558 --> 00:41:33.868
And then finally, all of these results will be synthesized by the CSO agent, then

676
00:41:33.888 --> 00:41:36.088
presented back to the human user.

677
00:41:38.208 --> 00:41:41.868
So I want to illustrate then a case study to demonstrate the

678
00:41:41.888 --> 00:41:43.648
workings of this virtual biotech.

679
00:41:45.148 --> 00:41:48.908
So a specific question we asked the biotech

680
00:41:49.128 --> 00:41:52.608
agents is to help us to design therapeutic strategies for

681
00:41:52.668 --> 00:41:56.288
CD276, also called B7H3, as a target in lung

682
00:41:56.368 --> 00:41:56.808
cancer.

683
00:41:58.508 --> 00:42:02.188
So this is a transmembrane checkpoint inhibitor

684
00:42:02.248 --> 00:42:06.208
protein, which has emerged in recent years as a very exciting

685
00:42:06.268 --> 00:42:06.728
target.

686
00:42:08.248 --> 00:42:11.258
So the first thing that the virtual biotech agent did is that it started to look at

687
00:42:11.288 --> 00:42:12.428
some genetics evidence

688
00:42:13.248 --> 00:42:16.978
and actually found that there's really not very strong genetic evidence around this

689
00:42:17.008 --> 00:42:20.388
target. But then the agents reasoned that that's okay

690
00:42:20.988 --> 00:42:24.868
because this is a target that's more relevant in tumor cells, whereas a lot of the

691
00:42:24.888 --> 00:42:28.508
genetics is looking at the germline mutations.

692
00:42:28.568 --> 00:42:31.628
So then the agents pivoted and decided to look at single-cell data.

693
00:42:32.748 --> 00:42:33.848
So it first pulled

694
00:42:35.088 --> 00:42:39.028
single-cell data from different cell atlases from tissues that are relevant to lung

695
00:42:39.088 --> 00:42:39.508
cancer.

696
00:42:40.428 --> 00:42:43.968
And by analyzing those single-cell data, it found that this

697
00:42:44.008 --> 00:42:47.688
target is particularly highly expressed in tumor-associated

698
00:42:47.748 --> 00:42:51.098
fibroblastsRight? And based on that, the agents

699
00:42:51.318 --> 00:42:54.818
came up with a hypothesis that

700
00:42:54.858 --> 00:42:57.978
perhaps these tumor-associated fibroblasts are expressing this

701
00:42:58.938 --> 00:43:02.658
checkpoint inhibitor, which then has the effect of suppressing the

702
00:43:02.698 --> 00:43:05.497
immune response in their surrounding cells.

703
00:43:06.758 --> 00:43:10.538
So to test that hypothesis, the agent next decided to perform a

704
00:43:10.578 --> 00:43:12.338
cell-cell communication analysis.

705
00:43:13.178 --> 00:43:16.918
By analyzing receptor ligand pairs, the agent actually found that

706
00:43:16.998 --> 00:43:20.328
indeed, these tumor-associated fibroblasts have a lot of

707
00:43:20.398 --> 00:43:23.338
communications with all the different major immune cell types.

708
00:43:24.178 --> 00:43:27.938
But here is where the agent reasons that, okay, to really confirm

709
00:43:28.138 --> 00:43:31.788
that in cell-cell communication, this will be really

710
00:43:31.788 --> 00:43:35.458
useful to actually analyze spatial data to really sort of be able to

711
00:43:35.498 --> 00:43:38.238
visualize these patterns of these

712
00:43:38.938 --> 00:43:40.158
immune-suppressing effects.

713
00:43:41.318 --> 00:43:44.378
And this is where the spatial analysis becomes really useful.

714
00:43:44.618 --> 00:43:47.598
So to do this, the agent actually found and downloaded

715
00:43:47.878 --> 00:43:51.278
these spatial transcriptomic datasets

716
00:43:52.038 --> 00:43:52.738
from Visium.

717
00:43:53.858 --> 00:43:57.778
And by analyzing this dataset, the agents actually showed

718
00:43:57.838 --> 00:44:00.958
that indeed in areas where

719
00:44:01.698 --> 00:44:05.118
these fibroblasts are expressing this P7H3

720
00:44:05.538 --> 00:44:08.858
protein, the surrounding neighborhoods are systematically

721
00:44:08.898 --> 00:44:11.598
depleted of different immune cell types.

722
00:44:12.108 --> 00:44:13.678
So there's quite a significant effect.

723
00:44:14.398 --> 00:44:18.098
So this actually really supports the agent's hypothesis

724
00:44:18.418 --> 00:44:22.178
that indeed that these fibroblasts are expressing this target,

725
00:44:22.598 --> 00:44:25.917
and then which has the effect of suppressing the immune response in their

726
00:44:25.958 --> 00:44:26.538
neighborhoods.

727
00:44:27.858 --> 00:44:31.218
And then finally, the agents are able to then connect all of this together with

728
00:44:31.278 --> 00:44:32.978
human clinical cohorts.

729
00:44:33.838 --> 00:44:37.378
So we look at cohorts of patients from lung cancer that are

730
00:44:37.778 --> 00:44:40.258
expressing this target either at a high level or a low level.

731
00:44:40.318 --> 00:44:44.218
And so by stratifying this target expression, the agents actually

732
00:44:44.298 --> 00:44:47.978
found that patient cohorts that express these targets

733
00:44:48.038 --> 00:44:51.778
highly are less responsive to different treatments, as

734
00:44:51.798 --> 00:44:55.398
measured both in terms of overall survival and also disease-specific

735
00:44:55.478 --> 00:44:55.998
survival.

